dark.gc is a library for working with GC.

  `Na`(`Vx`, `Vy`):    `Nadds` transaction of `Vx` GC with memo flag `Vy`
  `Nb`():        `Nbalance` as a number
  `Nc`():        amount `Ncached` in bank
  `Nd`(`Vx`):       `Ndetermine` latest transaction from balance, with memo flag `Vx`
  `Ne`:          (not yet used)
  `Nf`:          (not yet used)
  `Ng`(`Vx`):       `Ngets` all or just `Vx` GC from bank script
  `Nh`(`Vx`):       `Nhides` all or just `Vx` GC in bank
  `Ni`(`Vx`, [`Vy`]):  transaction `Nindices` near time `Vx`, or between `Vx` and `Vy`
  `Nj`:          (not yet used)
  `Nk`:          (not yet used)
  `Nl`():        `Nledger` of latest 100 transactions, for ease of use
  `Nm`(`Vx`):       converts string time `Vx` to integer `Nminutes`
  `Nn`(`Vx`):       `Nnumeric` version of `Vx` GC
  `No`:          (not yet used)
  `Np`:          (not yet used)
  `Nq`:          (not yet used)
  `Nr`():        `Nreasonable` balance; rounds down to lowest power of 10
  `Ns`:          (not yet used)
  `Nt`(`Vx`):       `Ntext` version of `Vx` GC
  `Nu`:          (not yet used)
  `Nv`(`Vx`, `Vy`):    `Nviews` transaction `Vx`, or transactions `Vx` to `Vy`
  `Nw`:          (not yet used)
  `Vx`(`Vx`, `Vy`, `Vz`): `Ntransfers` all or just `Vy` GC to `Vx`, with memo `Vz`
  `Ny`:          (not yet used)
  `Nz`:          (not yet used)
  `N$`:          (not yet used)
  `N_`:          (not yet used)

this library tries really hard to cache its values, assuming that you only use
this library for managing GC within scripts where it's used. it also allows
operating with a rudimentary `Nbank` script, which follows the below spec:

`Nbank` accepts one argument, `Namount`, which can be assumed to be a
nonzero integer. this "amount" represents the net change to the bank's balance;
if given a negative number, it should transfer GC to the caller, and if given a
positive number, it should transfer GC to the bank. this assumes that the
transfer happens immediately when the script exits, in one transaction, for
exactly the given amount, without failure, without a memo. almost always, this
is not actually a specialised "bank" but a secondary user which can temporarily
hold GC, whose balance is not maxed out. as a good rule of thumb, do not
request more money from the bank than you have offered to it in a single script
run.

here's a sample bank script, that meets these criteria:

  function(`Nc`, `Na`) {
      if (`Nc`.`Ncaller` != `V"your_user"` || !`Na`) return
      `Na` = `Na`.`Namount`
      `Na` > `V0`
          ? #ms.`Faccts`.`Lxfer_gc_to`({ `Nto`: `V"``Cbank_user``V"`, `Namount`: `Na` })
          : #fs.`Faccts`.`Lxfer_gc_to_caller`({ `Namount`: -`Na` })
  }
